<div id="review_2831165060" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2831165060" />
    <a title="Rex Fuller" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/11874992-rex-fuller"><img alt="Rex Fuller" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1345908061p2/11874992.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2831165060?book_show_action=true">May 23, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Rex Fuller" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Rex Fuller" href="/user/show/11874992-rex-fuller">Rex Fuller</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2831165060" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer11083615799504537437">You probably cannot legitimately claim knowledge of the Civil War -- at least not out loud -- without having read Shelby Foote&apos;s masterpiece which, tragically, probably could not be published today. You see it is by a Southerner, an honest one, who does not simply apologize for and condemn slavery as demanded by today&apos;s Red Guards in publishing and the media. Instead, here is an intelligent and original telling of the whole agony and valor.<br/><br/>The three volumes, I) Sumter to Perryville, II) Frederic</span>
  <span id="freeText11083615799504537437" style="display:none">You probably cannot legitimately claim knowledge of the Civil War -- at least not out loud -- without having read Shelby Foote's masterpiece which, tragically, probably could not be published today. You see it is by a Southerner, an honest one, who does not simply apologize for and condemn slavery as demanded by today's Red Guards in publishing and the media. Instead, here is an intelligent and original telling of the whole agony and valor.<br /><br />The three volumes, I) Sumter to Perryville, II) Fredericksburg to Meridian, and III) Red River to Appomatox, each almost run the length of "War and Peace." And you can't read any of it without thinking about the contents. It's a minor career. But so worth it.<br /><br />I doubt anyone who reads this will ever again think of the principal actors -- Lincoln, Davis, Stanton, Grant, Lee, McClellan, "Stonewall," and many others -- without seeing them in the light cast by Foote. He measures all and spares none. Just one example: you'd think that Lee would tower above the others in a true Southerner's treatment. Not so. Foote details many faults in Lee's personality, abilities, and actions.<br /><br />This gives you the feeling that you finally grasp the interweaving forces of international relations, politics, generalship, faith, foible, and fiasco that drove the many, many events of the War.</span>
  <a data-text-id="11083615799504537437" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


